Pattern 3: Set Based (Pure Existence)
You don't care where the element is, and you don't care how many times it appears. You just need $O(1)$ lookups to answer: "Does this exist?"The Concept: Use a HashSet (which is technically just a HashMap where the values are dummy objects).FAANG Trap: LeetCode 128 (Longest Consecutive Sequence) is a notorious FAANG question. You dump all numbers into a HashSet. Then, to find sequences, you only start counting when you find a number where num - 1 does NOT exist in the set (meaning it is the absolute start of a sequence).
Java Blueprint:
Java
Set<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();
for (int num : nums) set.add(num); // Dump everything in

for (int num : set) {
    // Only process if this is the START of a sequence
    if (!set.contains(num - 1)) {
        int currentNum = num;
        int currentStreak = 1;
        
        while (set.contains(currentNum + 1)) {
            currentNum += 1;
            currentStreak += 1;
        }
    }
}

Essential Interview Questions:
Easy: Contains Duplicate (LeetCode 217)
Easy: Intersection of Two Arrays (LeetCode 349)
Medium: Longest Consecutive Sequence (LeetCode 128) - Highly tested!
